"Client code that I use, probably can be improved. Only a small subset of all particle names use the notion \"bar\" to distinguish particle from antiparticle. For most particles it is sufficient to give the charge.\r\n```\r\n            if abs(p.pid) in {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 12, 14, 16, 2212, 2112}:\r\n                if p_db.bar:\r\n                    pname += \"~\"\r\n            elif p.pid in {21, 22, 23}:\r\n                pass\r\n            else:\r\n                pname += {2: \"++\", 1: \"+\", 0: \"0\", -1: \"-\", -2: \"--\"}.get(p_db.three_charge / 3)\r\n```\r\nParticles which are their own antiparticles should be better detected...\n\nHi @HDembinski, funny enough I have been looking at the same issues.\r\nI agree that the names need to be improved.\r\n\r\nThe problem is a bit more profound, I think, and I need to discuss with @henryiii on how to improve things from inside-out. For a start, some of the attributes of the `Particle` class are a 1-to-1 match to the fields of the PDG table. I think we do not need to expose all that to the user. BTW, the reason why some properties do not have docstrings, as you point out in https://github.com/scikit-hep/particle/issues/50, comes from a limitation in `attrs`, which does not provide an easy way to add a docstring to `attr.ib(`).\r\nTake the example of `name` and `fullname`. name can be the same for entries which correspond to particles with more than one charge possible; say a rho. I would make `name` hidden/private and would expose `fullname` as `name` \u2026 There is more to it here but let me now try and write it all down. Better discuss in person \u2026\r\n\r\n\r\nOn something related: we also need to have `programmatic_name` match the names we defined in the literals. That seems the best option to me.\r\n\r\nThis all needs some work. It won't take 1 day to get it all improved. It will be a great improvement, though ... which explains why I've been looking at the same things as you ... ;-)\r\n\r\n\n\nDocstrings can only be attached to classes or members of classes, but not to instance variables, which is what attrs is. That is, in this case `Simple.x` can have a docstring, but it is incorrect design, it is not a class instance:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nclass Simple:\r\n    x = something\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhile in this example, value.x cannot have a docstring, but is correct design:\r\n\r\n```\r\nclass Simple:\r\n    def __init__(self, something):\r\n        self.x = something\r\n\r\nvalue = Simple(something)\r\n```\r\n\r\nWhat you can do, however, is handroll documentation as part of the class docs (and attrs may eventually have a way to generate this, that is technically possible but a bit tricky).\r\n\r\nThere is a property or two that could be quite useful in cleaning up the fullname. It's worth some effort to see what we can do.\n\nHey, we didn't even have quarks added to Particle until quite recently :)"